Defense Response to Cause Shown for Elapsed Deadlines

It is clear to the defense, and it should be clear to this Court, that the State is seemingly not interested in prosecuting this claim. See State of Mayflower v. Kiannabailey022, Docket No. CR-0085-25 (M.D.C. 2025), where the State's failure to meet a deadline was held to mandate dismissal for failure to prosecute. A disclosure providing only two witnesses and a video clip should never be lateespecially when the deadline is clearly shown in (in a chart) by the minute orders of this Court. Despite having the deadline publicly available, and a ping to notify the Attorney General of its imposition, the State had seemingly decided that it need not familiarize itself with the deadlines set by this Court.

Instead, the State submits its discovery late (on the very gracious mercy of the Court to allow its submission at all) and submits it's reason (singular): this case had been forgotten by the State. While a hard-working law enforcement officer sits here with his career at risk, the State hopes or perhaps expects that their disclosures will be accepted and that the case will be allowed to proceed.

To allow the late-submission to stand unsanctioned provides numerous undue benefits to the Stateincluding the ability to simply 'forget' about cases until it's too late, and be redeemed anywayswhich are completely contrary to the rights of the defendant. I implore the Court to remember that my the defendant is not a mere number to be cast aside in the name of government convenience, but a living, breathing person who has rights that the government is obligated to respect. They did not do so today, and the matter should be dismissed for failure to prosecute accordingly.
